The article discusses a memorandum issued by Barack Obama on January 21, 2009, regarding the Freedom of Information Act (FOIA). Obama emphasizes the importance of transparency and accountability in a democracy. He states that the FOIA is a significant expression of the commitment to an open government. The memo emphasizes that the government should presume openness and disclose information, rather than keeping it confidential due to potential embarrassment or fear. Obama directs the Attorney General to issue new guidelines for the FOIA, reaffirming the commitment to transparency. He also instructs the Director of the Office of Management and Budget to update guidance for agencies to improve information dissemination to the public. The memorandum concludes by stating that it does not create any enforceable rights or benefits against the United States.